had-travelled-to-dubai-1660660-2020-03-28|date=28 March 2020|work=indiatoday.in|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| 2\n| 68\n| Male\n| [[Thiruvananthapuram]]\n| [[Government Medical College, Thiruvananthapuram]]\n| No\n| {{failure|Died on 31 March}}\n| The patient was on ventilator support for five days. He had suffered cardiac arrest and paralysis attack while on the life support system. Until now, it is not clear how he had contracted the disease. He had no recent history of foreign travel and according to close relatives, had not come into contact with infected persons.<ref>{{cite news |title=Second COVID-19 death in Kerala: Man with no travel history dies in capital|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2020/03/31/second-coronavirus-death-kerala.html|date=31 March 2020|work=manoramaonline.com|language=en}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=68-year-old man dies of coronavirus in Kerala, second death in state: Govt|url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/68-year-old-man-dies-of-coronavirus-in-kerala-second-death-in-state-govt/articleshow/74905482.cms|date=31 March 2020|work=indiatimes.com|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%\"\n|+ style=\"font-size:11pt;\" |{{nowrap|Details for Keralites COVID-19 cases who died outside Kerala (As of 2 April 2020)}}\n! Case order\n! Age\n! Gender\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Native\n! style=\"width:190px;\"| Country (Death)\n! style=\"width:100px;\"| Status\n! Note\n|-\n| 1\n| 85\n| Female\n| [[Ernakulam]]\n| {{flagdeco|United States}} [[New Jersey]], [[United States]]\n| {{failure|Died}}\n|\n|-\n| 2\n| 63\n| Male\n| [[Kannur]]\n| {{flagdeco|India}} [[Mumbai]], [[India]]\n| {{failure|Died on 1 April}}\n| The patient of [[Thalassery]] native who was a resident of Saki Naka, near [[Andheri]] died at [[Rajawadi Hospital]] in [[Ghatkopar]] after being admitted for four days by experiencing fever and severe throat pain.<ref>{{cite news |title=Keralite diagnosed with COVID-19 dies in Mumbai|url=https://keralakaumudi.com/en/news/news.php?id=274719&u=keralite-diagnosed-with-covid-19-dies-in-mumbai|date=31 March 2020|work=keralakaumudi.com|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| 3\n| 67\n| Male\n| [[Thrissur]]\n| {{flagdeco|United Arab Emirates}} [[Dubai]], [[United Arab Emirates]]\n| {{failure|Died on 1 April}}\n| The patient of [[Kaipamangalam]] native contracted the disease while undergoing treatment at the Rashidiya Hospital, [[Dubai]] for other ailments.<ref>{{cite news|title=Thrissur native dead|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/thrissur-native-dead/article31231848.ece|date=1 April 2020|work=thehindu.com|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| 4\n| 80\n| Male\n| [[Malappuram]]\n| {{flagdeco|United Kingdom}} [[London]], [[United Kingdom]]\n| {{failure|Died on 1 April}}\n| The patient of [[Perintalmanna]] native died in [[London]]. He was a doctor worked in [[West Midlands (region)|West Midlands]].\n|-\n| 5\n| 43\n| Male\n| [[Pathanamthitta]]\n| {{flagdeco|United States}} [[New York City|New York]], [[United States]]\n| {{failure|Died on 1 April}}\n| The patient hailing from [[Elanthoor]] was admitted to the hospital after experiencing severe fever. He was an employee at [[Metropolitan Transportation Authority|New York Metropolitan Transport Authority]] and was working at transit and was hospitalized following corona virus infection.<ref>{{cite news|title=Keralite dies in US due to coronavirus infection|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/nri/keralite-dies-in-us-due-to-coronavirus-infection-1.4659197|date=1 April 2020|work=mathrubhumi.com|language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| 6\n| 28\n| Male\n| [[Kannur]]\n| {{flagdeco|Saudi Arabia}} [[Medina]], [[Saudi Arabia]]\n| {{failure|Died on 4 April}}\n| The patient hailing from [[Panoor]] died at Saudi German Hospital, [[Medina]].<ref>{{cite news|title=A native of Panur, died in Saudi due to COVID 19|url=https://panoor.openmalayalam.com/?p=6506|date=4 April 2020|work=openmalayalam.com|language=Malayalam}}</ref>\n|-\n| 6\n| 52\n| Male\n| [[Idukki]]\n| {{flagdeco|United States}} [[New York City|New York]], [[United States]]\n| {{failure|Died on 5 April}}\n| The patient native of [[Thodupuzha]] died in the most effected state in the [[United States]], the [[New York City]].<ref>{{cite news|title=Another Malayalee dies of Kovid-related disease in US \u2013 Asianet News|url=https://www.mbs.news/c/2020/04/another-malayalee-dies-of-kovid-related-disease-in-us-asianet-news.html|date=5 April 2020|work=mbs.news|language=en}}</ref>\n|}\n\n==See also==\n* [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in India]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic}}\n{{2020 coronavirus pandemic in India}}\n\n[[Category:2020 coronavirus pandemic in India by state or union territory|Kerala]]\n[[Category:Health in Kerala]]\n[[Category:2020s in Kerala]]\n[[Category:Disasters in Kerala]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Details of the pandemic in the Indian state of Kerala}}\n{{Current event|2=current disease pandemic|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=March 2020}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox pandemic\n| name            = [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] in [[Kerala|Kerala, India]]\n| width           =\n| map1            = Kerala-COVID-19-map.svg\n| legend1         = Map of districts with confirmed cases (as of 2 April 2020)\n{{legend|#d45500ff|30+ confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ff9955ff|10\u201329 confirmed cases}}\n{{legend|#ffe6d5ff|1\u20139 confirmed cases}}\n| disease         = [[COVID-19]]\n| virus_strain    = [[SARS-CoV-2]]\n| location        = [[Kerala]], [[India]]\n| first_case      = [[Thrissur]]\n| arrival_date    = 30 January 2020<br>({{Age in years, months, weeks and days|month1=01|day1=30|year1=2020|month2=|day2=|year2=}})\n| origin          =\n| confirmed_cases = 306<ref name=\"GoKDB\">{{cite web |title=Kerala : Covid-19 Battle |url=https://dashboard.kerala.gov.in/index.php |accessdate=4 April 2020 }}</ref>\n| active_cases    = 254<ref name=\"GoKDB\"/>\n| recovery_cases  = 50<ref name=\"GoKDB\"/>\n| deaths          = 2<ref name=\"GoKDB\"/>\n| territories     = Entire state\n| total_ili       =\n| website         = {{url|http://dhs.kerala.gov.in}}\n}}\nThe [[2019-2020 coronavirus pandemic]] was first confirmed in India on 30 January 2020, in the state of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite news |last1=Narasimhan |first1=T. E. |title=India's first coronavirus case: Kerala student in Wuhan tested positive |url=https://www.business-standard.com/article/current-affairs/india-s-first-coronavirus-case-kerala-student-in-wuhan-tested-positive-120013001782_1.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Business Standard India |agency=Business Standard |date=30 January 2020}}</ref><ref name = weather>{{cite news |title=Kerala Defeats Coronavirus; India's Three COVID-19 Patients Successfully Recover |url=https://weather.com/en-IN/india/news/news/2020-02-14-kerala-defeats-coronavirus-indias-three-covid-19-patients-successfully |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=The Weather Channel |agency=Weather Channel |publisher=TWC India Edit Team}}</ref> As of 4 April 2020, there have been 306 confirmed cases with 50 recoveries and 2 deaths, more than 1,71,000 people are under surveillance in the state.<ref name=\"ectimes\"/><ref name =theweek>{{cite web |title=Kerala's robust health system shows the way to tackle coronavirus |url=https://www.theweek.in/news/india/2020/03/04/keralas-robust-health-system-shows-the-way-to-tackle-coronavirus.html |website=The Week |accessdate=9 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The cases were reported from travellers coming from China and Italy and their contacts.<ref name=\"ectimes\">{{cite news |title=3-yr-old from Kerala becomes first child in India to test positive for coronavirus |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/three-year-old-from-kerala-becomes-indias-40th-coronavirus-case/articleshow/74545428.cms |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=9 March 2020}}</ref>\nMany precautions are taken by the government to control the disease from spreading. Exams have been postponed, including the final school board exams, and all educational institutions will remain closed until the disease is wiped out. The government announced complete shutdown of the state from 23 March till 31 March. Public transport will not operate during this period, and public gatherings are restricted.<ref name = \"Shutdown\"/> A stimulus package of Rs 20,000 crore ($2.85 billion) has also been announced.<ref name = \"Stimulus\"/> On 28 March, a 69-year-old man from [[Mattancherry]], [[Ernakulam]] who had a travel history to the [[Middle East]], became the first person to die of Covid-19 in [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.businesstoday.in/latest/trends/coronavirus-india-cases-deaths-live-updates-lockdown-delhi-mumbai-america-italy-covid19-virus/story/399465.html|title=Coronavirus in India Live Updates: Kerala's first COVID-19 death; positive cases surge to 873\n|work=businesstoday.in|date=28 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Governmental actions==\n[[File:Healthcare workers wearing PPE 03.jpg|thumb|Healthcare workers wearing personal protective equipment for caregiving for a patient with coronavirus infection in a government hospital in Kerala.]]\nThe government of Kerala declared high alert from 4 to 8 February and starting 8 March 2020 due to coronavirus cases being reported from the state.<ref name = ecfeb8/><ref name = gulfnews/>  Isolation wards with 40 beds were set up in 21 major hospitals of the state and a helpline was activated in every district.<ref>{{cite news |first1=Jeemon |last1=Jacob |first2=Sonali |last2=Acharjee |title=How Kerala tamed the Coronavirus |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/magazine/up-front/story/20200224-how-kerala-tamed-the-coronavirus-1646259-2020-02-14 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref> As of 9 March, more than 4000 persons are under home or hospital quarantine in Kerala.<ref name=\"ectimes\"/> As of 4 March, 215 health care workers were deployed across Kerala and 3,646 tele counselling services were conducted to provide psycho-social support to families of those suspected to be infected.<ref name =theweek/> Despite the threat of coronavirus infection, the Kerala government decided to go ahead with ''[[Attukal pongala]]'', a large, annual, all-women religious congregation in [[Thiruvananthapuram]]. The government also urged individuals to refrain themselves from the ''pongala'', take precautions against disease transmission and, if possible, offer ''pongala'' at their own homes.<ref name = indiatodaymar9 /><ref>{{cite news |title=As coronavirus cases surge, Kerala put on high alert |url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/as-coronavirus-cases-surge-kerala-put-on-high-alert-11583736369396.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Livemint |date=9 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The government of Kerala has started a YouTube channel for updating the public regarding the status of coronavirus spread in Kerala and precautions to be taken.<ref>{{cite web |title=Kerala Health Online Training |url=https://www.youtube.com/channel/UCSE0zP8darFGvDn3CyC2ERg |website=YouTube |accessdate=9 March 2020 |language=en}}</ref> There are three coronavirus testing centres in Kerala : National Institute of Virology Field Unit, [[Thiruvananthapuram Medical College]], [[Calicut Medical College]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus test in India: Complete list of testing sites for coronavirus in India {{!}} India News - Times of India |url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/52-testing-sites-for-coronavirus-in-india/articleshow/74547684.cms |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=The Times of India |agency=The Times of India |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 10 March, the Kerala government arranged special isolation wards in prisons across the state.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kerala jails to set up isolation cells for suspected coronavirus-infected inmates |url=https://www.aninews.in/news/national/general-news/kerala-jails-to-set-up-isolation-cells-for-suspected-coronavirus-infected-inmates20200310102829/ |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=ANI News |language=en}}</ref> On 10 March, the government of Kerala shut down all colleges and schools up to grade 7.<ref>{{cite web |title=Coronavirus: Six fresh cases reported in Kerala; Schools, colleges, cinemas shut till March 31 |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/lifestyle/health/coronavirus-six-fresh-cases-reported-in-kerala-schools-colleges-cinemas-shut-till-march-31/1894165/ |website=The Financial Express |accessdate=11 March 2020 |date=10 March 2020}}</ref> The government also urged people to not undertake pilgrimages, attend large gatherings such as weddings and cinema shows.<ref name = mar10/>\n\nAlso, the government has launched a mobile application called GoK Direct for users to get information and updates regarding the COVID-19 (coronavirus) disease. It is an initiative from the Kerala Startup Mission and the Information & Public Relations Department. The app can also send text message alerts to basic phones (without internet).<ref>{{cite news |title=Kerala govt launches mobile app for users to track coronavirus updates |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/kerala-govt-launches-mobile-app-users-track-coronavirus-updates-120104/ |accessdate=13 March 2020 |work=The News Minute News |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 15 March, a new initiative 'Break the Chain' was introduced by Government of Kerala.The campaign aims to educate people about the importance of public and personal hygiene.\nUnder this campaign, the [[Pinarayi Vijayan]]-led government has installed water taps at public spots such as at the entry and exit gates of the railway stations with hand wash bottles.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kerala govt launches break the chain initiative for personal hygiene |url=https://www.ndtv.com/kerala-news/kerala-launches-break-the-chain-campaign-to-combat-coronavirus-2196103%3famp=1&akamai-rum=off|accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=NDTV |language=en}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 March, Chief minister [[Pinarayi Vijayan]] announced a stimulus package of Rs 20,000 crore ([[Euro|\u20ac2.5 billion]]; [[US Dollar|$2.6 billion]]) to help the state overcome both the covid-19 epidemic and economic hardship caused by it. This includes Rs. 500 crore for healthcare, Rs 2,000 crore for loans and free rations,  Rs 2,000 crore for creating jobs in rural areas, Rs 1,000 crore for families with financial difficulties, and Rs 1,320 crore for paying two months pensions in advance.<ref name = \"Stimulus\">{{cite news | last = Sneha Mary Koshy | title = 1 More Tests Positive For Coronavirus, Kerala Announces Rs 20,000 Crore Package | newspaper = NDTV | location = | pages = | language = English | publisher = NDTV | date = 20 March 2020 | url = https://www.ndtv.com/kerala-news/coronavirus-1-more-tests-positive-kerala-announces-rs-20-000-crore-package-2197698 | access-date = 25 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news\n | last = | title = Kerala government announces Rs 20,000 crore package to tackle coronavirus outbreak\n | newspaper = Hindustan Times | location = | pages = | language = English | publisher = Hindustan Times | date = 20 March 2020 | url = https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/kerala-government-announces-rs-20-000-crore-package-to-tackle-coronavirus-outbreak/story-KzGvehTH4HXjhnkTBLU49M.html | access-date = 25 March 2020}}</ref> The government has also ordered salons and workout centres to shut down. This is in order to prevent the virus from spreading via direct contact.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/health/health-news/2020/03/09/covid-19-local-transmission.html |title=\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d21\u0d4d\u2013 19; \u0d15\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u0d2f\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d7e \u0d15\u0d41\u0d31\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d41 \u0d38\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d40\u0d7c\u0d23\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d23\u0d4d, \u0d17\u0d57\u0d30\u0d35\u0d24\u0d30\u0d35\u0d41\u0d02 |access-date=2020-03-19 |language=ml}}</ref>\n\nOn 22 March, Health mister of Kerala, [[K. K. Shailaja]] strongly warned to people to follow the orders from Health department of [[Kerala]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.mathrubhumi.com/news/kerala/people-must-follow-directions-of-govt-k-k-shailaja-1.4635662|title=People must follow directions of Govt: K K Shailaja|website=Mathrubhumi|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\nOn 23 March, Chief minister [[Pinarayi Vijayan]] announced a statewide lockdown till 31st of march to prevent further spread of [[Coronavirus]].Being strictly applied in [[Kasargod]] necessary shops like grocery stores were allowed to be opened till 11am till 5pm. And in other districts necessary shops were opened from 7 am till 5 pm with the exception of medical stores. Public transports were shut down. There was no restriction for private vehicles but district to district travels were only allowed with thorough checking.<ref name = \"Shutdown\">{{cite web|url=https://www.asianetnews.com/kerala-news/covid-19-pinarayi-vijyan-announce-lock-down-in-kerala-q7ncg5|title=\u0d15\u0d47\u0d30\u0d33\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d7d \u0d32\u0d4b\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d21\u0d57\u0d7a; \u0d38\u0d02\u0d38\u0d4d\u0d25\u0d3e\u0d28\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d4d \u0d07\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d 28 \u0d2a\u0d47\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d \u0d15\u0d4a\u0d35\u0d3f\u0d21\u0d4d, \u0d15\u0d3e\u0d38\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d4b\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d4d\u0d25\u0d3f\u0d24\u0d3f \u0d05\u0d24\u0d40\u0d35 \u0d17\u0d41\u0d30\u0d41\u0d24\u0d30\u0d02|website=Asianet News Network Pvt Ltd|accessdate=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Quarantine==\nKerala is the only state in India that mandates 28 days of home quarantine for those returning from countries affected by coronavirus, while the national guidelines for India is 14 days.<ref name =theweek/><ref>{{cite news |title=How Travelers Around the World Are Dealing With 'Voluntary' Home Quarantines Over Coronavirus Fears |url=https://time.com/5785258/china-coronavirus-home-quarantine/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Time |language=en}}</ref> People who are advised home quarantine are advised to stay at their homes during the 28-day period, and report to healthcare authorities if they show symptoms of coronavirus infection.<ref>{{cite news |title=Another Wuhan University Student from Kerala Tested Positive with Novel Coronavirus |url=https://www.news18.com/news/india/another-wuhan-university-student-from-kerala-tested-positive-with-novel-coronavirus-2484719.html |work=News18}}</ref>\n{{2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic data/India/Kerala medical cases chart}}\n\n==Misinformation and conspiracy theories regarding coronavirus==\n{{main|Misinformation related to the 2019\u201320 coronavirus outbreak}}\nFollowing the reports of coronavirus infection in Kerala, fake news regarding prevention, transmission and cure for coronavirus infection started circulating on the internet, particularly on the social media platform Whatsapp.<ref>{{Cite news |url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/health/health-news/2020/03/19/corona-virus-transmission-mental-health-support.html |title=Jostin Francis \u2018\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d31\u0d4b\u0d23 \u0d2d\u0d40\u0d24\u0d3f\u2019 \u0d28\u0d3f\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d46 \u0d35\u0d40\u0d7c\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d41\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d41\u0d23\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d4b? \u0d07\u0d24\u0d3e \u0d1a\u0d3f\u0d32 \u0d2a\u0d30\u0d3f\u0d39\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d19\u0d33\u0d4d\u200d |access-date=2020-03-19 |language=ml}}</ref><ref name= aljazeerafakenews >{{cite news |title=Misinformation, fake news spark India coronavirus fears |url=https://www.aljazeera.com/news/2020/03/misinformation-fake-news-spark-india-coronavirus-fears-200309051731540.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=aljazeera.com}}</ref>\n\nOne fake message claiming to be an advisory from UNICEF asks people to avoid ice creams to ensure that coronavirus cannot spread in temperatures over 27 degrees.<ref name=\"aljazeerafakenews\" />\n\n[[T. P. Senkumar]] posted on social media that virus cannot survive in the hot and humid conditions in Kerala because the temperature there is over 27 degrees.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Madhu |first1=Aami |title=\u0d15\u0d4a\u0d31\u0d4b\u0d23 \u0d15\u0d47\u0d30\u0d33\u0d24\u0d4d\u0d24\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d46 \u0d1a\u0d42\u0d1f\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u200d \u0d35\u0d30\u0d3f\u0d32\u0d4d\u0d32\u0d46\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d28\u0d4d \u0d38\u0d46\u0d28\u0d4d\u200d\u0d15\u0d41\u0d2e\u0d3e\u0d30\u0d4d\u200d; \u0d2a\u0d4a\u0d33\u0d3f\u0d1a\u0d4d\u0d1a\u0d1f\u0d41\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d3f \u0d21\u0d4b\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d1f\u0d31\u0d41\u0d1f\u0d46 \u0d15\u0d41\u0d31\u0d3f\u0d2a\u0d4d\u0d2a\u0d4d |url=https://malayalam.oneindia.com/news/kerala/tp-senkumar-about-corona-virus-243241.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=malayalam.oneindia.com |date=6 March 2020 |language=ml}}</ref> Another fake news recommends intake of vitamin C and drinking frequent sips of water as a preventive measure for coronavirus infection.<ref name=\"aljazeerafakenews\" />\n\nAnother post on Facebook claimed falsely that if someone takes a deep breath and holds their breath for more than 10 seconds without coughing, without discomfort, stiffness or tightness, etc., it proves there is no (COVID-19 caused) fibrosis in the lungs, therefore indicating no infection.<ref name= 10secondsrule >{{cite news |title=Fact check: Will holding your breath for 10 seconds reveal if you have coronavirus? |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/news/factcheck/2020/03/22/coronavirus-fact-check-your-holding-breath-test-covid-19/2891572001/ |accessdate=23 March 2020 |website =USA Today }}</ref>\n\nThe claim that the vibration generated by clapping together during Janata curfew will kill the virus was debunked by the media.<ref>{{cite news |title=Mohanlal, many others share fake info that \u2018clapping may kill virus\u2019, PIB debunks |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/mohanlal-many-others-share-fake-info-clapping-may-kill-virus-pib-debunks-120844 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref> One viral message says that the lifetime of coronavirus is only 12 hours and staying home for 14 hours during Janata curfew break the chain of transmission. Another message claimed that observing Janata curfew will result in the reduction of coronavirus cases by 40%.<ref>{{cite news |title=Fact Check: Social media users give misleading twist to PM Modi's concept of 'Janta curfew' |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/fact-check/story/social-media-users-give-misleading-twist-pm-modi-janta-curfew-1658195-2020-03-21 |accessdate=23 March 2020 }}</ref>\n\n==Economic loss==\nTourism industry is a major contributor to the state's economy. Following coronavirus confirmation in Kerala, there were waves of cancellations of hotel bookings and tour packages.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.livemint.com/news/india/coronavirus-live-update-two-chinese-nationals-quarantined-in-hyderabad-11580994153313.html|title=Coronavirus India live update: All 645 evacuees from Wuhan test negative|date=6 February 2020|work=Livemint|accessdate=9 March 2020|language=en}}</ref>  Liquor sales in Kerala is a public sector undertaking, through which the government earns a significant revenue. However, following the outbreak, the sales have gone down, directly hitting the economy. The state's economy is largely dependent on [[Non-resident Indian and person of Indian origin|NRI]] remittances and the economic slowdown of affected Gulf countries is expected to have a direct impact.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/business/news/2020/03/11/covid-19-will-impact-kerala-economy-says-thomas-isaac.html|title=COVID-19 will impact Kerala economy, says Thomas Isaac|website=OnManorama|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref> [[Kerala State Road Transport Corporation|KSRTC]], Kerala's state-owned public transport system has reported losses worth crores due to reduced number of travelers.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/kerala/steps-to-cushion-economic-fallout-of-covid-19/article31085818.ece|title=Kerala initiates steps to cushion economic fallout of COVID-19|date=2020-03-17|work=The Hindu|access-date=2020-03-19|others=|language=en-IN|issn=0971-751X}}</ref> The practice of social distancing has also brought down the numbers of those who go out on weekends or do shopping, thus affecting local traders and vendors.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.freepressjournal.in/india/from-empty-beaches-to-cancelled-bus-services-how-coronavirus-has-impacted-keralas-economy|title=From empty beaches to cancelled bus services, how coronavirus has impacted Kerala's economy|website=Free Press Journal|language=en|access-date=2020-03-19}}</ref>\n\n==Timeline of events==\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"font-size:85%\"\n|-\n! style=\"width: 6%;\" | '''January'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''30 January''' ||\n* '''3 Cases''': The first positive cases of coronavirus in India were reported from three students of Kerala origin, travelling from the Wuhan province of China, which was the point of origin of the disease.<ref name = weather/><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Over 3000 people still under observation, says govt |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-over-3000-people-still-under-observation-says-govt/articleshow/74034608.cms |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=The Economic Times |date=8 February 2020}}</ref> They belonged to [[Thrissur district|Thrissur]], [[Alappuzha district|Alappuzha]] and [[Kasaragod district|Kasargod]] districts of Kerala and two of them were medical students at a University in Wuhan.<ref name = ecfeb8>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: Over 3000 people still under observation, says govt |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/politics-and-nation/coronavirus-over-3000-people-still-under-observation-says-govt/articleshow/74034608.cms |work=The Economic Times |date=8 February 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus outbreak: Third virus case reported from Kerala, student who returned from Wuhan tests positive |url=https://www.financialexpress.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-third-virus-case-reported-from-kerala-student-who-returned-from-wuhan-tests-positive/1855081/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=The Financial Express |date=4 February 2020}}</ref> Following the detection of positive cases, the government of Kerala declared a 'state calamity warning'. Over 3000 contacts of the affected individuals were placed under quarantine, out of which 45 were placed in hospital quarantine.<ref name = ecfeb8/> The three positive individuals later recovered from the infection following hospital care.<ref name=\"quartz\">{{cite news |last1=Kurian |first1=Oommen C. |title=How an Indian state successfully fought and contained the deadly coronavirus |url=https://qz.com/india/1802684/indias-kerala-defeated-deadly-coronavirus-using-information/ |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=Quartz India |agency=Quartz |publisher=Quartz India |date=14 February 2020 |language=en}}</ref> The 'state calamity' warning was withdrawn after 4 days, when no further cases were reported. As China was a popular country for students from Kerala to pursue medicine, several medical students got stranded in China when the lock-down due to coronavirus was put into effect. Some of them, who were stranded in airports in China were evacuated and flown into [[Cochin International Airport]] and quarantined at isolation wards in [[Kochi Medical College]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus: 15 students stranded in China brought to Kochi |url=https://www.thehindu.com/news/national/coronavirus-15-students-stranded-in-china-brought-to-kochi/article30766469.ece |work=The Hindu |date=8 February 2020 |language=en-IN}}</ref> However, none of them were later tested positive for the disease.\n! style=\"width: 12%;\"| Total Cases (3)<br>Recovered (3)<br>Death (0)\n|-\n! rowspan=\"20\" style=\"width: 6%;\" | '''March'''\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''8 March''' ||\n* '''5 Cases''' : The positive cases were a couple and their 26-year-old son, who had returned to Kerala from Italy.<ref name= italyfamily>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Cases In India Rise To 39, Centre Bans Foreign Cruise Ships: 10 Points |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/5-of-family-infected-with-coronavirus-in-kerala-total-positive-cases-in-india-rise-to-39-2191757 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> Two more people who had come in contact with the family also tested positive for the disease. They were kept under quarantine in [[Pathanamthitta district|Pathanamthitta]] General Hospital.<ref name = italyfamilycontact>{{cite news |title=Coronavirus Outbreak Highlights: Arunchal Pradesh Suspends Entry Of Foreigners Amid Coronavirus Scare |url=https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/coronavirus-outbreak-live-updates-3-new-cases-takes-total-to-34-in-india-2191698 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=NDTV.com}}</ref> The family had evaded health check-ups and had visited several other places during the one week they had spent in Kerala.<ref>{{cite news |title=Kerala family test positive for coronavirus, but did not reveal they had visited Italy |url=https://www.gulftoday.ae/news/2020/03/08/kerala-family-test-positive-for-coronavirus-but-did-not-reveal-they-had-visited-italy |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=gulftoday.ae}}</ref> Following this, the government issued a 'high alert'.<ref name = indiatodaymar9>{{cite news |last1=KochiMarch 9 |first1=india today digital |last2=March 9 |first2=india today digital |last3=Ist |first3=india today digital |title=3-yr-old from Kerala tests positive for coronavirus, total cases now 40 |url=https://www.indiatoday.in/india/story/child-kerala-tests-positive-coronavirus-total-cases-india-1653826-2020-03-09 |work=India Today |language=en}}</ref>\n! rowspan=\"20\" | Total Cases (238)<br>Recovered (21)<br>Death (2)\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''9 March''' ||\n* '''1 Case''' : A 3-year-old child, who had returned with his parents from Italy tested positive.<ref name = gulfnews>{{cite news |title=As coronavirus cases surge, Kerala put on high alert |url=https://gulfnews.com/world/asia/india/as-coronavirus-cases-surge-kerala-put-on-high-alert-1.1583752066135 |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=gulfnews.com |language=en}}</ref> The parents and the child were shifted to the isolation ward at Ernakulam Medical College.<ref name = indiatodaymar9 />\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''10 March''' ||\n* '''8 Cases''' : Six individuals who were in contact with the family who had returned from Italy were confirmed to have the coronavirus infection. Four of the new cases were admitted at [[Kottayam]] and in [[Kozhencherry]]. The infected individuals were the grandparents of the affected couple, two from a family they had visited in [[Ranni]] and two relatives who picked the couple up from the airport.<ref name = mar10>{{cite news |url=https://www.thenewsminute.com/article/12-coronavirus-cases-kerala-grandparents-family-italy-test-positive-119892 |title=12 coronavirus cases in Kerala, grandparents of family from Italy test positive |accessdate=10 March 2020 |work=thenewsminute.com}}</ref> Later, the parents of the 3-year-old infected child, who were put in isolation in Ernakulam Medical College tested positive, taking the total number of cases in Kerela to 17.<ref name=active14>{{cite web|url=https://www.hindustantimes.com/india-news/2-more-cases-of-coronavirus-in-kerala-14-infected-in-state-so-far/story-ZbTl7p3NkehEIrH6dY61iL.html|title=2 more cases of coronavirus in Kerala, 14 infected in state so far|work=Hindustan Times|access-date=11 March 2020|date=10 March 2020}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''12 March''' ||\n* '''2 Cases''' : It was confirmed that two persons with travel history from Middle East tested positive for the virus. One, who is from Kannur, had a travel history to Dubai and the other, from Thrissur, had traveled from Qatar. On 13 March 3 people tested positive 1 Italian in Varkala and 2 persons in Trivandrum. No new cases reported on March 14.<ref name = middleeasttravel>{{cite news |title=Two more coronavirus cases reported in Kerala, number up to 16 |url=https://www.outlookindia.com/newsscroll/two-more-coronavirus-cases-reported-in-kerala-number-up-to-16/1759500 |accessdate=12 March 2020 |work=Outlook}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''13 March''' ||\n* '''3 Cases''' : Three more persons, a Keralite who returned from Dubai on Thursday after visiting many countries, including Italy; a tourist from Italy who was under observation at a private resort at Papanasam in Varkala in Thiruvananthapuram; and a Keralite who returned from United Kingdom were tested positive.<ref name = manoramaonline>{{cite news |title=were tested positive |url=https://english.manoramaonline.com/news/kerala/2020/03/13/coronavirus-covid19-cases-kerala-pinarayi-vijayan-italian-kollam.html |accessdate=9 March 2020 |work=english.manoramaonline.com |language=en}}</ref>\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''15 March''' ||\n* '''2 Cases''' : A foreigner from Britain who was staying in [[Munnar]], and another a doctor in Trivandrum who had returned from Spain.<ref name = DeccanHerald>{{cite news |title=New 2 more coronavirus cases reported in Kerala |url=https://www.deccanherald.com/amp/national/dubai-national-doctor-test-positive-in-kerala-total-tally-in-the-state-rises-to-21-813937.html|accessdate=15 March 2020 |work=Deccan Herald}}</ref> On 16 March, 3 more cases were confirmed by the Chief Minister of Kerala. One in [[Kasargod]] who had visited Dubai and two cases in [[Malappuram]] who went to Saudi Arabia bringing the total number of cases to 24.\n|-\n| style=\"text-align:center;\"| '''16 March''' ||\n* '''3 Cases''' : Three cases have tested positive; one in Kasaragod and two in Malappuram. All the three are said to be Gulf returnees.<ref name = Manoramaonline>{{cite news |title=3 more Coronavirus+ cases in Kerala, laxity a major concern